name: NATMAN
description:
Forget Katman.

This is NATMAN.

REPLACEMENTS

Knight fills in the early must-break slots of SMC and Testrun/Femme

Djinn fills in for SMC->Datasucker

Liberated accounts are 5 virtually magnum clicks per copy without installation cost(think about it), giving efficiency that you lost from not having Professional Contacts

WHAT IT DOES BETTER

Knight and Grimoire->Datasucker means it's harder to get locked out of servers

Stimhack trashes Sansan, shrinks maxhandsize for Sweeps Week, and fully pays for Katman's biggest expense, Atman for 4(or more)

More memory with Djinn and Grimoire means you can play Datasuckers, Atmans, and still have space for juice like Parasite/Medium/Imp

Trash cards when you play datasuckers

name: Rush Kit
The Mutalisk v1.0
description:
Mutate is a very interesting card, except for the fact that the best ice is hardly the one developed by Jinteki Corporation. So to better exploit this card one has to spend a lot of influence into acquiring big and bad ice from other factions.

My selection has been the following:

  • Archer: simply because it's still the number one ice on the market, if you ask me. Not to mention the possibility to ignore the forfeiting of an agenda was too good to pass.
  • Heimdall 2.0: is quite expensive to break and taking some brain damage against Jinteki can be a bad choice and become extremely dangerous the more the game drags on. It also can't be broken entirely with clicks (or at least not easily!).
  • Janus 1.0: again, brain damage is the one thing you don't wanna accumulate against the scary oriental corporation, and 4 subroutines ensure you either break or get at least 1 (most of the time).

No ice from NBN because Tollbooth might be awesome, but it's too much of an easy target for Femme Fatale and it doesn't really pose a threat to the runner's life. Maybe to his economy, but not to his life and with Personal Evolution I like to at least try achieving a flatline.

Having almost no barriers (only 2 you should rez only with Mutate anyway) means their Fracter will be nearly useless, since most of the ice is naturally of the Sentry type. There's also 3 cheap and Yog.0-targetable Code Gates, but there's also two Lotus Field and one Inazuma which might require a bit more effort from the Runner.

It might be worth adding Chum because with Mutate you install the new ice in the same position of the one you trashed, therefore possibly placing it under an empowering Chum. That would be nice.

There's enough small ice to sacrifice and hopefully avoid a starting hand with no ice to protect HQ and/or R&D. Still, R&D is dangerous enough that maybe they won't run so carelessly. In case you have too many of those cheap pieces of ice left in R&D to use mutate successfully, there's also a couple Precognition to help out.

I chose to add plenty of traps so you can play the shell game while fortifying your HQ and R&D, and a Psychic Field mostly to try and scare that nasty expose away. Also one Cerebral Overwriter to increase the sources of the oh-so-good-brain damage.

Economy is a bit tight, so scoring an early Gila Hands Arcology is a big plus (well, it always is, right?), but of course House of Knives if a big plus too.

Well, it's still a deck in a very early stage, so any comment or suggestion is greatly appreciated. ;)

name: RP in peace v1
description:
An RP kill deck that's been in development since the recent reconsideration of Hunter on reddit. Lots of ways to put the runner in a bad position-- Psychic Field + Cerebral Static with a backup of Scorched Earth is the surest way, but with lots of taxing ICE and relatively few agendas, the runner will often make mistakes. This version had (expensive but) relatively scorable agendas with penalties to the runner for taking them; I've been playing with only 7 agendas (3 The Future Perfect, 3 Priority Requisition and a Fetal AI) which makes it nearly impossible to score out, but a really tough nut to crack which you wait for that flatline window.

Hunter and Data Raven are surprisingly good at stopping a runner in their tracks. Tsurugi should be put wherever the runner most wants to get in-- likely centrals. Snowflake makes for great Sundew protection-- cheap and just enough to make the runner think twice. Alternatively Hunter gives you a chance to tag them as they come in last click to kill a rezzed asset.

Try to draw very little. Don't tip your hand and show your Jacksons-- it's easy to get caught with too many agendas and you need that defence, as well as protection against Indexing. Take it slow & steady.

name: Wayland Advancement Test Deck v1
Norton AntiVirus Can't Help You Now
description:
Hey Guys,

The idea behind this deck is to trash enough cards utilizing Noise's identity that even if Archives is iced up in the end I use Stimhack to help my ice get past whatever I need to.

I feel like I have been staring at this deck too long and I have become blind to the tweaks that may really help so any suggestions would be great.

name: Noise BURST
Thank you for the credits, the ones I'm using.
description:
Since I read about Nasir, I got really excited. I'm not a big fan of running. Building runner decks were always a hassle for me and never really turned out well, but this guy changed things. He changes the way the runner plays and how the corp plays (for the most part).

This deck is all about keeping a low credit pool, hoarding reoccurring credits and making money off of your opponent. I've been playing this deck for a while and has provided some great games. Unfortunately, it's not strong in early game, but mid- late game, it runs fantastic.

The deck itself, I think, is pretty easy to play. Just keep in mind to keep your credit pool low. Increase the rez cost by Xanadu and Rook. Use Snitch to scout ice. If you don't like what you see, jack out.

There are very few economy cards in this deck for a reason. Keep running at ice, if you hit an "end the run" subroutine after a just rezzed ICE take it and play more cards from your grip.

name: The Origin Of Iain
description:
Now I know what you're thinking. No wait, you could be thinking one of several things like:

Why is your deck 49 cards? Why did you spend 6/10 influence on one of the worst breakers in the game? Why do you only have X copies of X?

Well the answer to those questions is I'm bad at deck theory. What I am good at, however, is playing Iain Sterling. I'm also bad at spelling his last name.

This deck hasn't lost yet. Now, granted, I've only played it 5 times on OCTGN, and 2 of those times my opponent didn't know I'd be playing a current, but hell - they count.

Most of this deck is classic Iain. Gather up your homies and then plan big game-winning plays with Legwork. Find Kati Jones and Mr. Li as fast as possible, set up your Access to Globalsec / Underworld Contact combo and your Oracle May / Motivation. Maybe most importantly get your Logos out as soon as possible. Use Fall Guy to keep New Angeles City Hall around so you don't get Sea Sourced since this deck doesn't run Plascretes.

The tricky part of this deck are the breakers. You want to get Darwin out a couple of turns before you think they're going to start making moves. Then you let him grow. You want to use the core breakers as last resorts - keep Femme and Darwin going for maximum efficiency. You're going to be getting 2-5 creds a turn anyway, so the hit on Darwin doesn't really hurt you in the long run. Also if they spend a turn wiping virus counters - GREAT! There's many more things that this deck would rather be doing than running, and the corp just gave you a free turn to do that. (This is a great time to play those core breakers and hit them with an unexpected siphon).

And remember, it's not the deck - it's the pilot. So you have to be as bad as the deck to pilot it correctly.

name: Nasir, ICE Explorer
Jonah and D4v1d
description:
Darwin and D4v1d pair up as the primary breakers. Mimic is there to provide an additional way to face-check if you can't get Darwin/Djinn out quickly. It also serves as Swordsman insurance.

I went with Helpful AI over Personal Touch as a way to boost Darwin/Mimic on the fly, but also as a nice little link buffer for the Spinal Modem.

I went with Demolition run over Imp because I feel like Imp just invites more virus purges, and by the time I'm setup for a massive Imp run with Medium, I could probably pull off a Demolition Run.

I'm not really sure how the economy is going to work, but Kati feels right given the slow buildup of Darwin.

Other notes:

  • The Datasucker wasn't initially a key part of my strategy, so that's why there's only 1. Thinking about just putting in that third Parasite instead but I feel weird running without any suckers at all.

  • The Compromised Employee was just my 1-influence throw-in that seems to pair well with Spinal Modem and general econ.

  • Scrubbed could also be seen as a hindrance for D4v1d, so I may replace that with another current depending on how well it works.

  • I am still a somewhat newer player and still catching up on datapacks, etc. There may be some cards I don't even have that would make more sense here :)

name: Because They Said I Wouldn't Build It
description:
This is the newest build of the Weyland Consortium: Because We Built It Deck I've been working on.

I was finding issues drawing enough ICE, so I've tried to swap in some more ICE. Tollbooth is powerful enough that I feel confident spending the influence on it, and the Rototurrets will force the runner to find a Killer of an AI breaker to get into the server.

I had also previously not had any Tag punishment in the deck, so my opponents were floating Tags all over the place. I removed the Commercializations to put in a set of Scorched Earth that should discourage that sort of play.

name: Encore v1.0
description:
Okay, so, still pretty new to this; this is the deck I've been fiddling with for the past week or so. It wants to play through as much of the deck as you can afford to - clicking for credits only rarely and drawing as many cards as you can as quickly as you can.

Basic idea is pretty simple: get to two Link using Access to Globalsec, then use a combination of your lots of card draw (Diesel, Quality Time) and Hostage to draw out your three copies of Underworld Contact. Now you have reliable recurring cash.

Ice tends towards the expensive side, but that's mitigated by using the Test Run/Scavenge trick; thanks to your identity, this nets you at least one and possibly two cards (depending on where the program starts). If you're having trouble drawing enough of one or the other of those (you will), you can use Same Old Thing to fill in the gaps.

Everything else is there either in support of those two goals. Kati Jones gives you one recurring source of cash, in addition to your 3 credits/turn, and can also be fetched by a Hostage if need be; with seven non-redundant Connections in the deck, Calling in Favors made good sense. Other cards are there either for money (Sure Gamble, Stimhack) or protection (Feedback Filter, Plascrete Carapace, New Angeles City Hall, Infiltration). Fall Guy makes a lot of the other work more sustainable: you can protect Kati, hang on to that one Same Old Thing your deck has coughed up, or keep the New Angeles City Hall around.

Feedback very welcome!
